* [[Olof Palme Prize]] (2005)
* Doctor of Laws [[Honorary degree|(honoris causa)]] from [[Memorial University of Newfoundland]] (2004)&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.mun.ca/senate/Honorary_graduates_by_convocation.pdf|format=PDF|title=Honorary Graduates of Memorial University of Newfoundland|date=4 June 2008|accessdate=2008-06-04 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080625040405/http://www.mun.ca/senate/Honorary_graduates_by_convocation.pdf |archivedate = 25 June 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt;
* [[Four Freedoms Award|Freedom from Fear award]] (2006)&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.feri.org/common/news/info_detail.cfm?QID=1983&amp;ClientID=11005|title=Recipients of the Four Freedoms Award|accessdate=2008-12-24 |archiveurl = http://web.archive.org/web/20080621235756/http://www.feri.org/common/news/info_detail.cfm?QID=1983&amp;ClientID=11005 |archivedate = June 21, 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt;
* [[Honorary Canadian citizenship]] (2007)&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.cbc.ca/world/story/2007/10/17/burma-canadian.html?ref=rss Burma's democratic heroine named honorary Canadian] [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation]], 17 October 2007&lt;/ref&gt;
* Honorary President of the [[LSE Students' Union|LSESU]] (2007)&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.lsesu.com/pages/representation/honorary_president/ Aung Sang Suu Kyi Honorary President]{{dead link|date=November 2010}} London School of Economics Studies&lt;/ref&gt;
* Doctorate of Letters [[Honorary degree|(honoris causa)]] from [[Colgate University]] (2008)&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web | url = http://www.collegenews.org/x7907.xml | title = CBS News Journalist Lesley Stahl to Deliver Colgate's 2008 Commencement Address | date = 21 February 2008 | accessdate = 18 May 2008}}&lt;/ref&gt;
* [[Congressional Gold Medal]] (2008)&lt;ref&gt;[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/asia-pacific/7366357.stm US Senate honours Burma's Suu Kyi – BBC News] 25 April 2008&lt;/ref&gt;
* Premi Internacional Catalunya (2008)&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.gencat.cat/pic/eng/index_2008.htm|title=Daw Aung San Suu Kyi i Cynthia Maung, winners of the 20th edition of the Premi Internacional Catalunya}}&lt;/ref&gt;
* Honorary Member of the [http://www.clubmadrid.org/ Club of Madrid] (2008)
* Freedom Of [[Glasgow]] (2009)&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.burmacampaign.org.uk/index.php/burma/news/aung-san-suu-kyi-awarded-freedom-of-glasgow Aung San Suu Kyi Awarded Freedom of Glasgow], Burma Campaign, 5 March 2009&lt;/ref&gt;
* [[Mohandas Karamchand Gandhi|Mahatma Gandhi]] International Award for Peace and Reconciliation (2009)&lt;ref&gt;[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/NEWS/World/Rest-of-World/Suu-Kyi-wins-Gandhi-Peace-Award-in-SA/articleshow/4804856.cms Suu Kyi wins Gandhi Peace Award in South Africa] ''[[The Times of India]]'', 22 July 2009&lt;/ref&gt;
* [[Honorary degree|Honorary]] [[Doctor of Laws]] from [[University of Ulster]] in recognition of her services to human rights (2009)&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.ulster.ac.uk/summergraduation2009/pressreleases.html |title=University of Ulster Graduation Ceremonies – Summer 2009 |publisher=Ulster.ac.uk |date=7 July 2009 |accessdate=2010-09-30}}&lt;/ref&gt;&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.ulster.ac.uk/summergraduation2009/News/4news7thJulyam.htm Ulster Honours Burmese Democracy Leader Aung San Suu Kyi] University of Ulster, June 2009&lt;/ref&gt;
* [[Ambassador of Conscience Award]] (2009) from [[Amnesty International]]&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://aappb.org/bio_pdf/Aung_San_Su_Kyi_bio_1_Oct_2009.pdf |title=Aung San Suu Kyi Profile |publisher=www.aappb.org |date=1 October 2009 |accessdate=2010-10-18}}&lt;/ref&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;

==Popular media==
* She was portrayed by [[Adelle Lutz]] in [[John Boorman]]'s 1995 motion picture ''[[Beyond Rangoon]]'', which takes place during the [[8888 Uprising]].
* In a list compiled by the British magazine ''[[New Statesman]]'' in 2006, she was voted as number one among the &quot;50 Heroes of Our Time&quot;. Other &quot;heroes&quot; mentioned were [[Nelson Mandela]], [[Noam Chomsky]], [[Bill Gates]], and [[Bono]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|last=Cowley |first=Jason |date=22 May 2006 |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/200605220016 |title= Heroes of our time&amp;nbsp;— the top 50 |work=New Statesman |accessdate=2006-05-22}}&lt;/ref&gt;
* The 2000 song &quot;[[Walk On (song)|Walk On]]&quot; by [[U2]] is about her, according to Bono.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.aungsansuikyi.com/about/bono-speaking-about-aung-san-suu-kyi/ Bono speaking about Aung San Suu Kyi]. Aungsansuukyi.com&lt;/ref&gt; During U2's 2009 tour, the band invited fans to wear masks of Suu Kyi's face (printable from their website) during the song &quot;Walk On&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.u2.com/news/title/walk-on Walk On]. U2.com. 26 June 2009.&lt;/ref&gt;
* The release of Aung San Suu Kyi is the subject of a [[Chrysler]] commercial featuring [[Nobel Prize]] laureates traveling in stylish black [[Chrysler 300]]s to the 10th Nobel Laureate summit in Berlin. However, one Laureate could not attend, Aung San Suu Kyi represented by an empty white Chrysler 300.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|url=http://www.phayul.com/news/article.aspx?id=26137&amp;article=Car+maker+calls+for+release+of+Aung+San+Suu+Kyi&amp;t=1&amp;c=1 |title=Car maker calls for release of Aung San Suu Kyi |publisher=www.phayul.com |date=6 December 2009 |accessdate=2010-09-30}}{{dead link|date=November 2010}}&lt;/ref&gt;
* ''The Lady Of Burma'', a play written by Richard Shannon and staged in the London Old Vic, dealt with the life of Aung San Suu Kyi and received rave reviews in the UK press, including ''[[The Independent]]''.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/theatre-dance/reviews/the-lady-of-burma-the-old-vic-london-424278.html |title=The Lady Of Burma, The Old Vic, London - Reviews, Theatre &amp; Dance |publisher=The Independent |date=14 November 2006 |accessdate=2010-11-13 |first=Kate |last=Thomas}}&lt;/ref&gt;
*She is mentioned in the State Radio song &quot;Bohemian Grove&quot;.
* She was voted as number 34 among &quot;The World's 50 Most Influential Figures 2010&quot; by the British magazine ''[[New Statesman]]''.&lt;ref&gt;{{cite web|title=Aung San Suu Kyi  - 50 People Who Matter 2010|url=http://www.newstatesman.com/international-politics/2010/09/suu-kyi-burmese-barred-burma}}&lt;/ref&gt;
* She will be portrayed by [[Michelle Yeoh]] in ''[[The Lady (2011 film)|The Lady]]'', a forthcoming film written by Rebecca Frayn and directed by [[Luc Besson]].&lt;ref&gt;{{cite news|author= Brown, Mark|author2=Simon Hattenstone|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/world/2010/dec/19/aung-san-suu-kyi-the-lady |title= Aung San Suu Kyi's tragic love and incredible life come to the big screen|work= The Guardian|date= 20 December 2010|publisher = Guardian News &amp; Media}}&lt;/ref&gt;
* &quot;Unplayed Piano&quot; by Damien Rice was released in Ireland on June 17, 2005 and in the UK on June 20, 2005 to coincide with Aung San Suu Kyi's 60th birthday. The song was written for Suu Kyi following a visit by Damien to Burma in July 2004. Proceeds from the sale of the single go to the [[Burma Campaign UK]]. Rice and Hannigan recorded a charity song, campaigning for her release, called &quot;Unplayed Piano&quot;, which they performed at the 2006 Nobel Peace Prize Concert in Oslo.&lt;ref&gt;http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Damien_Rice#Charity&lt;/ref&gt;

