'''Active Server Pages''' ('''ASP'''), also known as ''Classic ASP'' or ''ASP Classic'', was [[Microsoft]]'s first [[server-side scripting|server-side]] [[Active Scripting|script-engine]] for [[dynamic web page|dynamically-generated web pages]]. Initially released as an add-on to [[Internet Information Services]] (IIS) via the [[Windows_NT_4.0#Option_Pack|Windows NT 4.0 Option Pack]] (ca 1998), it was subsequently included as a free component of Windows Server (since the initial release of [[Windows 2000 Server]]). [[ASP.NET]] has superseded ASP.

ASP 2.0 provided six [[Wiktionary:built-in|built-in]] [[Object (computer science)|objects]]: Application, ASPError, Request, Response, Server, and Session. &lt;code&gt;Session&lt;/code&gt;, for example, represents a [[http cookie|cookie-based]] [[Session (computer science)|session]] that maintains the state of [[Variable (programming)|variables]] from page to page. The [[Active Scripting]] engine's support of the [[Component Object Model]] (COM) enables ASP [[website]]s to access functionality in compiled [[Library (computing)|libraries]] such as [[Dynamic-link library|DLLs]].

Web pages with the ''.asp'' [[file extension]] use ASP, although some web sites disguise their choice of scripting language for security purposes (e.g. still using the more common ''.htm'' or ''.html'' extension).
Pages with the ''.aspx'' extension use compiled [[ASP.NET]] (based on Microsoft's [[.NET Framework]]), which makes them faster and more robust than [[server-side scripting]] in ASP, which is interpreted at run-time; however, ASP.NET pages may still include some ASP scripting. The introduction of ASP.NET led to use of the term ''Classic ASP'' for the original technology.

Programmers write most ASP pages using [[VBScript]], but any other Active Scripting engine can be selected instead with the &lt;tt&gt;@Language&lt;/tt&gt; directive or the &lt;code&gt;&amp;lt;script language=&quot;language&quot; runat=&quot;server&quot;&amp;gt;&lt;/code&gt; syntax. [[JScript]] (Microsoft's implementation of [[ECMAScript]]) is the other language that is usually available. [[PerlScript]] (a derivative of [[Perl]]) and others are available as third-party installable Active Scripting engines.

==Alternative interpreters==
There only a few alternative interpreters, and most of them are implemented in Java. Unlike the Mono ASP.net implementation, these versions tend to be quite different compared to the Microsoft interpreter, which results that not all scripts written for the Microsoft platform may be supported.

Example of these are
* '''[[Sun ONE]] Active Server Pages'''&lt;br /&gt;This version is EOL, and the latest version cannot be downloaded anymore. Some older versions still exist on the web.
* '''[http://www.tripi.com/arrowhead Arrowhead ASP]'''&lt;br/&gt;This is an ASP implementation in for Java Servlet containers, but it seems to be abandoned (latest release is 0.2.3 on June 14, 2004
* '''[http://cfasp.cloudfoundry.com CloudFoundry ASP]'''&lt;br /&gt;This is basically a repack of the Arrowhead ASP implementation, but with updated libraries and optimalisations for the [[Cloud Foundry]] platform. It seems to be quite recent, but the differences with Arrowhead are little.


